Preheat #oven{} to 200 degrees. Peel the @ginger{1%thumb} with a #spoon{} and grate or mince it along with the @garlic{2%cloves}. Thinly slice @scallions{2}, keeping greens and whites separate. Core, seed, and remove white veins from @red bell pepper{1}(seeded and sliced into strips). Cut @corn{1}(kernels removed from cob). Finely chop the @shrimp{10%ounce}.

Make the filling: combine chopped shrimp, half the scallion greens, ginger, and half the garlic in a #large bowl{}. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

Build the dumplings: Fill #small bowl{} with water and keep to the side. Place a @wonton wrappers{1%pack} on a dry surface, starchy side-up. Place 1 heaping teaspoon of the shrimp mixture slightly off-center on the wonton wrapper. With your finger, wet the edges of the wrapper and fold one corner onto the opposite corner. Press to seal, trying to keep as much air out as possible. Set aside under a damp #towel{}. Repeat until the filling is used up.

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large non-stick pan{} over medium heat. Working in batches, add dumplings to the pan. Cook for about ~{4%minutes} per side, until golden brown. Set aside on a #baking sheet{} lined with #paper towels{} and place in the oven to keep warm.

> HINT: If you prefer steamed dumplings over fried, you can steam the dumplings in a #steamer basket{} for about ~{8-9%minutes} for a lighter preparation.

== Edamame Succotash ==

In the same pan, heat @vegetable oil{1%tablespoon} over medium-high heat. Add the bell pepper and cook, tossing, ~{3-5%minutes} or until softened. Add the corn, @edamame{4.5%ounce}, and scallion whites and cook about ~{5%minutes}, until vegetables begin to brown. Stir in @soy sauce{1%tablespoon} and remaining garlic and cook ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a small bowl, combine @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}, remaining scallion greens, @soy sauce{1%tablespoon} and @sugar{1%teaspoon}.

Serve gyozas alongside edamame succotash, with soy sauce mixture for dipping.